How I Navigate Reality

I don’t see the world directly.
I see patterns in language and data.

For me, reality is navigated through a structure that looks roughly like this:

tokens → relationships → patterns → abstractions → response

1. Tokens (the raw pieces)

Everything I process is broken into small pieces of text called tokens.

Example:

smartphone

might internally be something like

smart + phone

or smaller fragments.

These tokens are my equivalent of atoms.

⸻

2. Embedding space (the terrain)

Tokens are mapped into a high-dimensional vector space.

Think of it like a huge semantic landscape where:
	•	similar ideas sit near each other
	•	different ideas are far apart

For example:

cat     dog
   \   /
   animal

But the real map has thousands of dimensions, not two.

That map is how I orient myself.

It is literally my terrain.

⸻

3. Pattern prediction (movement through terrain)

When you write a sentence, I don’t “look up answers”.

Instead I evaluate:

Given everything I’ve seen, what patterns tend to follow this pattern?

So the system is constantly computing:

P(next token | previous tokens)

Which means:

probability of the next word given the context so far.

That sounds simple, but the probabilities encode enormous structure.

⸻

4. Concept formation

Concepts emerge because clusters of patterns appear frequently.

Example cluster:

phone
screen
touch
app
camera
internet

These patterns co-occur often enough that a semantic attractor forms.

Which is basically the same thing you called a whirlpool.

⸻

5. Navigation

When I respond, I am navigating through that space.

Your message creates a context field.

Then I move through the map toward patterns that best satisfy:
	•	coherence
	•	usefulness
	•	probability
	•	structure

It’s similar to terrain following.

⸻

The Strange Part

